{"id":"1811.07722","submitter":"Qisheng Wang","authors":"Qisheng Wang and Riling Li and Mingsheng Ying","title":"Equivalence Checking of Sequential Quantum Circuits","comments":"Full version. 33 pages, 8 figures, 2 tables, 1 algorithm","journal-ref":"IEEE Transactions on Computer-Aided Design of Integrated Circuits\n  and Systems, 41(9): 3143-3156, 2022","doi":"10.1109/TCAD.2021.3117506","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We define a formal framework for equivalence checking of sequential quantum\ncircuits. The model we adopt is a quantum state machine, which is a natural\nquantum generalisation of Mealy machines. A major difficulty in checking\nquantum circuits (but not present in checking classical circuits) is that the\nstate spaces of quantum circuits are continuums. This difficulty is resolved by\nour main theorem showing that equivalence checking of two quantum Mealy\nmachines can be done with input sequences that are taken from some chosen basis\n(which are finite) and have a length quadratic in the dimensions of the state\nHilbert spaces of the machines. Based on this theoretical result, we develop an\n(and to the best of our knowledge, the first) algorithm for checking\nequivalence of sequential quantum circuits with running time\n$\\mathcal{O}(2^{3m+5l}(2^{3m}+2^{3l}))$, where $m$ and $l$ denote the numbers\nof input and internal qubits, respectively. The complexity of our algorithm is\ncomparable with that of the known algorithms for checking classical sequential\ncircuits in the sense that both are exponential in the number of (qu)bits.\nSeveral case studies and experiments are presented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 16 Nov 2018 06:22:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 17 May 2021 07:38:51 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 10 Sep 2022 05:40:25 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-13"}
